               <head>Akbarnāmah. Vol. 1 by Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak</head>

               <msContents class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n80002413
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh85064913
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008115921
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008115920">

                  <summary>Volume 1, part 2 of the <title>Akbarnāmah</title> by Abū al-Faz̤l ibn
                     Mubārak. </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_168-item1">
                     <author key="viaf_5150639">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak,
                           1551-1602</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">أبو الفضل بن مبارك</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20880">Akbarnāmah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">اكبرنامه</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmala">(f.1v) سلسلهٔ
                        انتظام...</incipit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa"> (f. 294v): بتاریخ دوشنبه ۲۹ شهرِ محرمِ الحرام سالِ
                        بیست و دهم از جلوس پادشاهِ عدالت‌ پروردهٔ عالمگیر موافق سنهٔ ۱۰۹۸ حسن انجام
                        حسن انجام یافت تحریر فی‌التاریخِ غره صفر بوقت غر روزِ پنجشنبه سنهٔ ۴۳ جلوس
                        والا تحریر یافت</colophon>
                     <colophon>Completed on 29 Muḥarram regnal year 30 of ʿAlamgīr corresponding to
                        the year 1098 (15 Dec. 1686) and noted? <hi rend="italic">taḥrīr</hi>) on 1
                        Ṣafar regnal year 43 (29 July 1699). </colophon>
                     <note>The <hi rend="italic">khātimah</hi> begins on f. 281v, line 9.</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>

               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>ff.ii+294 <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>267</height>
                              <width>140</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>European foliation in pencil every fifth leaf. </p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>
                           <p>
                              <catchwords>Catchwords on the bottom-left corners of the verso.
                              </catchwords>
                           </p>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Fair. Some pages are damaged and worm-eaten. </p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="19">
                           <p>19 lines per page. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary/>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Nastaʻlīq; copied in black ink; marks and overlining in red. </p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>Folio 1r contains an explanation entitled <title>ḥarf-i abjad</title> of the
                           <hi rend="italic">abjad</hi> system of numbering. </p>
                     <p>Also on f. 1r, Richard Johnson's accession statement: <hi rend="italic">Az
                           mutamallakāt-i sarkār Fayz̤ al-ās̱ār Navvāb Ṣāḥib Mumtāz al-Dawlah
                           Mufakhkhar al-Mulk Ḥusām Jang Mistar Richārd Jānsan Ṣāḥib Bahādur dām
                           iqbāluh. </hi></p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1875" notAfter="1899">
                        <decoNote>Late 19th century full mottled leather covering on plain boards.
                        </decoNote>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal subtype="rectangle" type="stamp">
                        <p>Very badly preserved rectangular seal of former owner on flyleaf <locus from="iir" to="iir">iir</locus> <hi
                              rend="italic"><persName role="fmo" key="person_f8872">ʻIbād
                                 Allāh</persName> 1188</hi> (1774/75). </p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Oval East India Company Library stamp ff. <locus from="1r" to="1r">iir</locus> and ff. <locus from="294v" to="294v">iir</locus>: ‘E.I. Company
                           Library’. </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>

               <history>
                  <origin><origDate calendar="#Gregorian" when="1686-12-29">29 Muḥarram RY 30 of
                        ʻĀlamgīr 1098 AH (15 Dec. 1686)</origDate>
                     <origPlace>India</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Belonged to <persName role="fmo" key="person_f8872">ʻIbād Allāh</persName>
                        whose seal dated 1188 (1774/75) occurs on many manuscripts in the Johnson
                        Collection. </p>
                     <p>Acquired in India between 1770 and 1790 by the East India Company servant
                           <persName role="fmo" key="viaf_287207857">Richard Johnson</persName>, and
                        brought to England on his return. </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>The Johnson collection—comprising 64 albums of paintings and an estimated
                        1,000 manuscripts—was purchased by the East India Company Library for 3,000
                        guineas on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1807-02-18">18 February
                           1807</date>. </p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>

